# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-football-international
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The **AFL Commission** is the board of directors that governs the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Its chairman has been Richard Goyder since 4 April 2017.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 1985, the AFL (then named Victorian Football League Limited) formed the commission as a body independent of its member clubs, to operate its competition.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over from the AFL's board of directors, who had been representatives of its then-15 member clubs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council which had published the Laws of Australian Football.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL's constitution self-proclaims it to be the "keeper of the code" responsible for the sport of Australian football.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL operates the All-Australian team, World (formerly All-international) team and Australian Football Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL operates the premier professional Australian Football competition in Australia and the State of Origin competition (1991-1999 and 2026-present).
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Since 1998, it has also overseen Australia's involvement in the International Rules Series.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] An independent governing body for the competition was first moved in December 1984 during the fallout of VFL president Allen Aylett's resignation following the South Melbourne Football Club's financially disastrous relocation to Sydney.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The club, managed from Melbourne but playing in Sydney, had sustained substantial finanical losses in Sydney and large loans had been written out by the league to keep them viable, which was also impacting the finances of the competition.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Under its first chief commissioner, Jack Hamilton, the VFL began a restructuring toward a franchise model, whereby member clubs operate licenses owned by the league.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The model helped make private ownership of the Swans possible in 1985, as well as the sale of new licenses, resulting in the entry of the Brisbane Bears and West Coast Eagles in 1987.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Under the new model, many Melbourne clubs struggling for financial viability such as St Kilda, Fitzroy and North Melbourne could be kept afloat by a combination of private ownership and league subsidies from the sale of new clubs and television rights.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The restructuring paved the way for the VFL's expansion into a national competition.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Despite continuing financial troubles at many clubs, including the Swans and Footscray, the AFL was able to turn the competition's finances around by 1989, aided by increased television rights and the sale of $4 million licenses to interstate expansion clubs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 2014, all AFL players were fully-paid professionals for the first time in the competition's history.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL is governed by its board of directors, called the AFL Commission.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the Australian National Football Council, which ceased operations after 89 years of existence.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 2002, it took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 2010, it took over the operations of Women's Football Australia, which ceased operations in 2015.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL took over the operations of the New South Wales Australian Football League Limited, and the AFL subsidiary, AFL NSW/ACT now operates in Australia's most populous eastern state and the ACT.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL promotes and brands the sport under its own name rather than of the formal name of Australian Football.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are elected by the 18 AFL clubs, with each of the 18 clubs entitled to make nominations, but other Australian Football leagues, associations and clubs do not have any control or representation.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL approves new club franchise licenses to expand its competition.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Since 1987, it has been instrumental in the merger that created the Brisbane Lions, while the Sydney Swans were fully owned by the AFL, which retains a controlling interest and reversion rights in the event the Sydney Swans do not repay debts to the AFL.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL also fully owns the Greater Western Sydney Giants.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Other clubs to have an AFL appointed board include the Sydney Swans, the Gold Coast Suns, Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL operates a Competitive Balance Fund, which redistributes profits to the clubs most in need to help ensure that all of its member clubs are financially sustainable in the long-term.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL is financially dependent on the success of its competitions with the majority of its funding coming from the AFL competition broadcasting rights.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The 2025-2031 rights will earn $4.5 billion, the most lucrative in Australian sporting history.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL operates the Australian Football Hall of Fame, the AFL men's underage championships and AFL Women's underage championships.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] It is also responsible for senior State of Origin competition, which will return in 2026 after a 27-year hiatus.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL is administered by its commission of company directors, which sets policy and has directed the VFL/AFL (known then as the VFL) as the game's most professional league since December 1985.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 1993, the independent commissioners took over as the directors of the AFL from its Board of Directors, which had been appointed as delegates of its then 15 member clubs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The Board of Directors voted itself out of existence, and the AFL's then 15 member clubs also voted to abolish the old system of club appointment of directors and to adopt a new Memorandum and Articles of Association for the AFL.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] This was a significant change of power: between 1985 and 1993, the VFL/AFL had required explicit approval by a 75% vote of its member teams for major items such as further expansion, mergers, relocations, and major capital works.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 1995, the AFL took over the operations of the ANFC (see Principle 2 below).
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL also created an international policy in 2005 and took over the operations of the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Amateur and semi-professional Australian Football competitions across Australia are mostly self-sufficient from the AFL.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] These competitions, their clubs and teams often buy equipment and apparel that is AFL branded which provides revenue to the AFL.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Some junior competitions pay to use the AFL proprietary Auskick program and junior clubs pay the AFL for give-away packs at AFL run promotions in their localities.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL has established a pathway that features junior Academies and scholarships from representational level up to its member clubs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The highest level is the AFL Academy, with academies for each state being managed by their respective AFL clubs and affiliated governing bodies.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Between 2010 and 2021, the AFL spent between $6–38 million per annum (under 5% of total revenue) on game development grants globally (excluding a one-off COVID-19 Pandemic community football recovery package).
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] With a new TV rights deal in 2022 and to help the game at the grassroots continue its recovery post COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased its community grants to $67 million.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The ten commissioners are nominated and elected by vote of the 18 AFL member clubs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] A two-thirds majority of member clubs have the power to veto over commission decisions.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The commission elects its chairman and employs a chief executive officer to oversees the management and operations of the AFL.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] While the commission is responsible for directing AFL policy, it has, on occasions, become directly involved in on and off-field matters relating to AFL competitions, players, coaches and managers.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] Sometimes these interventions have been in controversial circumstances.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL owns a stake in the Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney clubs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The AFL manages a special fund called the Competitive Balance Fund (CBF) since 2004 as a grant of up to $5 million per club to ensure that member clubs remain financially viable.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] The system was later changed to the Annual Special Distribution (ASD) of $6.3 million shared among all clubs, as well as allowing for grants and special concessions, such as payments, to ensure that the AFL member clubs remain viable in the short term.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In 2006, the AFL approved a $2.1 million special financial assistance package for Carlton.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-commission] In early 2009, it increased Melbourne's assistance from $250,000 to $1 million and made a $1 million grant to Port Adelaide.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] AFL Europe also organises the European combine which provides a direct pathway to the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] Australian football has been played regularly in Europe since the late 1980s when leagues formed in England and Denmark.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] These first leagues led to the first international game between two European teams was played in 1994 between Great Britain and Denmark.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] As more leagues were formed, more international games began to be organised.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] Historical international competitions played by European teams include the Atlantic Alliance Cup, Central European Australian Football League Championships and the European Australian Football Tri-nations Tournament.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The growth of Australian football in Europe led to the need for a central body that was accountable to the member organisations.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] At the 2005 EU Cup a conference was held which formed the body *Aussie Rules Europe* as a promotional body.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] *ARE* was superseded after a conference at the 2009 EU Cup the decision was made to form such a body at another conference the following January.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The January conference was held in Frankfurt, Germany and the *European Australian Football Association* was founded.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] At an October, 2010 conference in Parabiago, Italy the members of the *EAFA* voted to change the organisations's name to *AFL Europe*, to fall in line with the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] Beginning in 2013 the annual Colleges and Universities Cup is named after current AFL Chairman, Mike Fitzpatrick.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] Generally played by Irish and English Universities and Colleges, with the 2016 edition being held in Birmingham for the second year running.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] A new event first held in March 2015, contested as a one-day lightning carnival involving the club champions of all the various European leagues.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The inaugural Champions League was won by the West London Wildcats in Amsterdam.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] Beginning in 2012 and played in Villers-Bretonneux to commemorate the ANZAC's and the historic liberation of the town in World War I by Australian forces.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] A team of Australian players selected based on their connection to the ANZAC heritage to play in a game against the France national team, which is a centrepiece of the annual commemorations.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The current tally stands at 4 wins to Australia and 3 wins to France.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] Starting in 2015, the first corporate event held by AFL Europe to raise awareness of Aussie Rules internationally was held in Australia House in London.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The function was run in conjunction with the South Australia Club and was hosted by Bill Muirhead (Agent General for South Australia and AFL Europe Ambassador).
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The ticketed event provided a unique opportunity for attendees to connect with the UK and Australian business communities while creating exposure for AFL Europe and our great game.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] An annual nine-a-side footy competition.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The Euro Cup was originally known as the *EU Cup*, the name was changed after teams representing non European Union countries started participating.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The Euro Cup is partially intended as a developmental tool to allow participation for countries without enough players to form a full team.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] Held every three years, this full format competition determines the Champions of Europe and has taken place twice since the inaugural championship in Denmark and Sweden in 2010.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The reigning champions are Ireland who won the most recent championship on home soil with a goal on the final siren against neighbours Great Britain, maintaining a 100% record in the Championships.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] AFL Europe also support a range of events and tournaments throughout the UK and Europe which can be seen in the Calendar on the AFL Europe Website.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The *Legion* represents the whole of Europe in Australian football.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The Legion's first game was an Under 21 game against the AFL-AIS Academy Australian Under 17 team in London, England.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The Europe team had only been together for three days, which showed in the **27.21 (183)**-**2.0 (12)** scoreboard.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-europe] The Legion's colours are the blue and gold of the Flag of Europe and white.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The sport is played at various levels, mainly by expatriate Australians.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The main cup competition played in the area is the Dubai 9s, although a regional league under the name **AFL Middle East** which commenced in October 2008, with the inaugural 2008/09 premiers being the Dubai Heat.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The AFLME initially featured six clubs, three in Dubai and one each from Abu Dhabi, Muscat and Doha.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Australian football is not known as a spectator sport in the Middle East.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The first Australian Football League exhibition match was played in the United Emirates in 2008.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The only matches broadcast are AFL matches (particularly the AFL Grand Final) on satellite television in some countries through the Australia Network and on cable television in Israel.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Bahrain Blues were created in 2009, making their debut at the Dubai 9s tournament that year.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] They will enter the AFL Middle East as the league's seventh club for the season starting in October 2009.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Servicemen, mostly Australians in Iraq played a game on ANZAC Day in 2008 in the colours of Essendon Bombers and Collingwood Magpies to celebrate The ANZAC Day clash.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Australian Rules in Israel has been played sporadically since the 1980s.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The earliest mentions of the sport were in the mid-1980s.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In the 1970s, there was no Aussie Rules, and expatriate Australian player David Stark took up rugby and playing in the lock position was part of the national rugby team in the 70s and 80s.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] By 1984 a small band of followers was noted to be playing informally in 1984 in Tel Aviv, Jerusalem and Yerucham parks.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In 1986, groups of 24 players from the British Olim Society gathered to play matches following viewing of television footage of the VFL Grand Final.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In 1995, when a group of around 20 players began regular social matches in Tel Aviv, although most of the players were based in Jerusalem.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] By 2005 the community was still playing with around 70 players involved and discussion about creating a four-team league with sides from Tel Aviv, Jerusalem and various youth programs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The majority of the playing base were the members of the Jewish community in Melbourne who have emigrated to Israel.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] For political reasons Israel is affiliated with the European chapter of the AFL organisation and participates in its events.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] A side representing Israel competed in both years of the Australian Football Multicultural Cup, winning the 2004 competition.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] A team composed of Australian Jews resident in London competed as Israel in the 2005 EU Cup.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Highlights of the AFL Grand Final have been shown on Fox Sports Israel.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] An idea to utilise the game Australian rules football as an instrument for forging peace between Israelis and Palestinians was suggested and carried out by Tanya Oziel of the Australian Jewish community in Sydney in late 2007.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Consequently the AFL Peace Team project was created by Tanya Oziel and curated by Peres Center for Peace and Innovation.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] This team was composed mainly of basketball and soccer players and volunteers, trained from scratch in the first half of 2008 to participate in 2008 Australian Football International Cup that took place in August 2018 in Australia.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The project received a wide support in Australian business, sport and social circles, including Australian Jewish businessman and Carlton Football Club president Dick Pratt and AFL legend Ron Barassi.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In early 2008 there were initially around 75 players in training for the team, which was cut back to around 26 (13 Israelis, 13 Palestinians) for the squad to attend the International Cup.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Match-day coach for the team at the tournament was former player Robert DiPierdomenico.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Peace Team also returned for the Australian Football International Cup in 2011.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] A few of the AFL Peace Team's graduates led by Yonatan Belik went on to establish the Jerusalem Peace Lions football club (JPL) in May 2015 continuing the peace effort.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Team's management was actively recruiting both Israeli and Palestinian players residing in Jerusalem and surrounding areas.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The club competed internationally representing Israel and the region in the 3 consecutive AFL Euro Cups 2015-2017.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In May 2018 a few former JPL players moved to Tel Aviv, and led by Shir Shalev started training in the Yarkon Park.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In August 2018 they partnered with the sports platform OddBalls and formed the Tel Aviv Cheetahs football club.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Cheetahs and OddBalls are more focused on developing the sport itself rather than the activist work previously done by Peace Team and JPL, aiming to embed Australian rules football into Israeli cultural context and attract more local players.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Prioritising the grassroots way of development the club's led to the club's squad being 3/4 Israeli.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] This allows the team to have a better chance at international European tournaments organised by AFL Europe, despite recent restrictions on the amount of Australian-born and raised participants allowed in the roster.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Being the only active footy club in the region in 2018, the club went on to represent Israel internationally at the AFL Euro Cup 2018 in Cork, Ireland.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In May 2019 OddBalls and the Tel Aviv Cheetahs' management formed a national team, the Israeli Beasts, aiming to represent Israel in the AFL Euro Cup 2019 that will take place on 29 June in Sweden.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In 2023, a team representing the Tel Aviv Cheetahs travelled to Bulgaria to participate in a four-team tournament.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The tournament also included two teams from London and a local Bulgarian team made up of players from the Sofia and Varna teams.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Later the same year, Israel hosted its first Australian Rules international tournament in the city of Be'er Sheva to commemorate ANZAC day. the tournament included two Israeli teams, a team from the United Arab Emirates, and a team representing the Vienna Galahs.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The tournament was won by the team from the UAE, and video from the tournament was hosted on the AFL's social media channels.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] A team representing the Melbourne Lebanese community also competed at the Australian Football Multicultural Cup in both 2004, 2005, 2010 & 2011, winning the cup three times and then a fourth in 2014.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Team Lebanon was taken over by new president and head coach Rick Kerbatieh, who successfully coached the team to its fourth Harmony Cup in 2014 and is preparing the team for the World Cup in 2015.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Rick has coached a record 10 grand final wins with team Lebanon.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Rick is currently looking at expanding the game in Lebanon once again and is working behind the scenes in an attempt to set up a Team Lebanon sporting academy.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In 2018, the inaugural Mediterranean Cup Team Lebanon came from behind and won the competition.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Lebanon also has a national Australian rules football team, nicknamed the "Lebanese Falcons".
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] A group of players from Oman appeared at the 2007 Dubai 9s.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Dubai Dingos followed the Dubai 9s by scheduling a match against the Omani side, which was partly composed of Gaelic football converts.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In 2008, the Muscat Magpies were formed as the country's first formal club.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Magpies compete in the upcoming AFL Middle East.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] An Australian rules football club nicknamed the Kangaroos was founded in Doha, Qatar in early 2007, with their first appearance being at that year's Dubai 9s tournament.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Squad is made up of expatriate Australians.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Doha Kangaroos were a founding member of the AFL Middle East.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] Australian Rules in the United Arab Emirates has been played since 2006, with the creation of a club in Dubai known as the Dubai Dingoes.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In addition to the senior team, there is junior football held weekly.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The club is mainly composed of expatriate Australians as well as Irish from the local gaelic football club.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Dingoes held a 9-a-side international tournament in early 2007, also featuring teams from Abu Dhabi, Oman and Qatar.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] A second and more successful club called the Dubai Heat was created in 2007.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] A team mainly drawn from the Dubai Heat, but also with some players from the Dubai Dingoes, represented the UAE at the 2007 Asian Australian Football Championships.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In 2008 Dubai Heat entered another team in the Asian championships and successfully took the title beating the Singapore Wombats.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] In February 2008, the first AFL match in the United Arab Emirates was held at the Ghantoot Polo and Racing Club in Abu Dhabi between the Adelaide Crows and the Collingwood Magpies.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] It was one of few official NAB Cup matches played outside of Australia and the game attracted a sell-out crowd of 6,102 using a makeshift field and grandstand and was televised free-to-air in Australia.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The curtain raiser for the AFL match was played between the Dubai Dingos and Dubai Heat.
[src:australian-football-international/afl-middle-east] The Abu Dhabi Falcons and Dubai Dragons were formed in 2008 as the UAE's third and fourth clubs.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:australian-football-international/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett was born in Melbourne on 24 April 1934.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He attended University High School in his hometown.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He made his debut for North Melbourne at the age of 17 while he was still in secondary school, a rare feat at the time.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] It was as an Australian rules football rover that Aylett first made his mark.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He played 220 games and kicked 311 goals, in a career spanning 1952–1964.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He won North Melbourne's best and fairest award from 1958 to 1960, was All-Australian in 1958 and 1961, won the Tassie Medal in 1958 (the first player from Victoria to win), won the Simpson Medal in 1960, and was captain of his side from 1961 to 1964.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He was selected in the North Melbourne Football Club's Team of the Century.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett also had a brief cricketing career that he never fully pursued due to his interest in Australian rules football.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He played as a batsman in 11 first-class matches in the 1950s for domestic cricket side Victoria but was not successful, finishing with a batting average of just 16.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He played district cricket for Carlton (two seasons) and University (six seasons), averaging 27.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett is best known for his career as an administrator in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett was elected president of the VFL in 1977.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He continued his aggressive efforts to push the game's administration towards professional and business-driven success.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] His actions in setting up the VFL's Night Series in 1977, as a direct rival to the NFL's Night Series, delivered both sponsorship opportunities and laid the platform for the VFL to supersede the NFL for control of football in Australia.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Under his guidance, the league expanded into the Sydney market, making preparations for an expansion team before South Melbourne opted to relocate there; Aylett subsequently sat on the Swans' board of directors.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett stepped down in December 1984 following the establishment of the VFL Commission.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett also served as president of the National Football League from 1978 until 1985.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He subsequently returned for a second and final stint as North Melbourne Kangaroos president from 2001 to 2005.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] In the 1979 Birthday Honours, Aylett was appointed an Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) for services to Australian rules football.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] On 24 October 2000, he was awarded the Australian Sports Medal for his contribution to Australian Football.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] On 1 January 2001, he was awarded the Centenary Medal for service to Australian society through the sport of AFL football.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] He was inducted into the Sport Australia Hall of Fame as an administrator in 2006.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett worked as a dentist throughout his career and into his eighties.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett was married to Marjorie "Marj" Wapet for 71 years until his death.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] They met while studying at University High together.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Together, they had four children: Tony, Rick, Julie and Sam along with 8 grandchildren and 5 great-grandchildren.
[src:australian-football-international/allen-aylett] Aylett died on 16 September 2022 at the age of 88.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The meaning and significance of Australia Day has evolved since the first records of celebration in 1808, with contested views on the day existing since at least 1888.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The first prominent protest also occurred around this time in 1938, with the first Day of Mourning held by the Australian Aborigines' League.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1994, the date was fixed in all jurisdictions on 26 January, with the practice by some states of holding the holiday on a Friday in late January for a long weekend dropped.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Since at least 1938, the date of Australia Day has also been a day of protest and of mourning the start of the British colonisation of Australia, characterised as an invasion in which Aboriginal Australians had the land that they had occupied for millennia forcibly taken.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Some observe 26 January as Invasion Day, Survival Day or as a Day of Mourning, as a counter-observance to the national day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Some counter-observers and others have called for the date of Australia Day to be changed or the holiday to be abolished entirely.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Support for changing the date has been a minority position over successive annual polls.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] A January 2026 Roy Morgan poll found 60.5% support for retaining 26 January as the date for Australia Day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] On 13 May 1787 a fleet of 11 ships, which came to be known as the First Fleet, was sent by the British Admiralty from England to New Holland.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Under the command of Naval Captain Arthur Phillip, the fleet sought to establish a penal colony at Botany Bay on the coast of New South Wales, which had been explored and claimed by Lieutenant James Cook in 1770.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The settlement was seen as necessary because of the loss of the Thirteen Colonies in North America.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The Fleet arrived between 18 and 20 January 1788, but it was immediately apparent that Botany Bay was unsuitable.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] They made contact with the local Aboriginal people, the Cadigal.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] On 21 January, Phillip and a few officers travelled to Port Jackson, 12 kilometres (7.5 mi) to the north, to see if it would be a better location for a settlement.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] They stayed there until 23 January; Phillip named the site of their landing Sydney Cove, after the Home Secretary, Thomas Townshend, 1st Viscount Sydney.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] On the morning of 24 January, the party was startled when two French ships, the *Astrolabe* and the *Boussole*, were seen just outside Botany Bay.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] This was a scientific expedition led by Jean-François de La Pérouse.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The French had expected to find a thriving colony where they could repair ships and restock supplies, not a newly arrived fleet of convicts considerably more poorly provisioned than themselves.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] On 25 January the gale was still blowing; the fleet tried to leave Botany Bay, but only HMS *Supply* made it out, carrying Arthur Phillip, Philip Gidley King, some marines and about 40 convicts; they anchored in Sydney Cove in the afternoon.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Meanwhile, back at Botany Bay, Captain John Hunter of HMS *Sirius* made contact with the French ships, and he and the commander, Captain de Clonard, exchanged greetings.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Clonard informed Hunter that the fleet commander was Jean-François de Galaup, comte de La Pérouse.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] *Sirius* successfully cleared Botany Bay, but the other ships were in great difficulty.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] *Charlotte* was blown dangerously close to rocks, *Friendship* and *Prince of Wales* became entangled, both ships losing booms or sails, *Charlotte* and *Friendship* collided, and *Lady Penrhyn* nearly ran aground.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Despite these difficulties, all the remaining ships finally managed to clear Botany Bay and sail to Sydney Cove on 26 January.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The last ship anchored there at about 3 pm.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Clearing of the ground for an encampment immediately began.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The formal establishment of the Colony of New South Wales did not however occur on 26 January as is commonly assumed.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] It did not occur until 7 February 1788, when the formal proclamation of the colony and of Arthur Phillip's governorship were read out.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The vesting of all land in the reigning monarch King George III also dates from 7 February 1788.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The 1808 celebrations followed this pattern, beginning at sunset on 25 January and lasting into the night, the chief toast of the occasion being Major George Johnston.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Johnston had the honour of being the first officer ashore from the First Fleet, having been carried from the landing boat on the back of convict James Ruse.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Despite suffering the ill-effects of a fall from his gig on the way home to Annandale, Johnston led the officers of the New South Wales Corps in arresting Governor William Bligh on the following day, 26 January 1808, in what became known as the "Rum Rebellion".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Almanacs started mentioning "First Landing Day" or "Foundation Day" and successful immigrants started holding anniversary dinners.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1818, the 30th anniversary of the founding of the colony, Governor Lachlan Macquarie chose to acknowledge the day with the first official celebration.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The governor declared that the day would be a holiday for all government workers, granting each an extra allowance of "one pound [450 grams] of fresh meat", and ordered a 30-gun salute at Dawes Point – one for each year that the colony had existed.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] This began a tradition that was retained by the Governors that were to follow.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Foundation Day, as it was known at the time, continued to be officially celebrated in New South Wales, and in doing so became connected with sporting events.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] One of these became a tradition that is still continued today: in 1837 the first running of what would become the Australia Day regatta was held on Sydney Harbour.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Happy with the success of the regatta, the organisers resolved to make it an annual event.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] However, some of the celebrations had gained an air of elitism, with the "United Australians" dinner being limited to those born in Australia.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The following year, 1838, was the 50th anniversary of the founding of the colony, and as part of the celebrations Australia's first public holiday was declared.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The regatta was held for a second time, and people crowded the foreshores to view the events, or joined the five steamers (*Maitland*, *Experiment*, *Australia*, *Rapid*, and the miniature steamer *Firefly*) to view the proceedings from the water.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] At midday 50 guns were fired from Dawes' Battery as the Royal Standard was raised, and in the evening rockets and other fireworks lit the sky.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The dinner was a smaller affair than the previous year, with only 40 in attendance compared to the 160 from 1837, and the anniversary as a whole was described as a "day for everyone".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Prior to 1888, 26 January was very much a New South Wales affair, as each of the colonies had its own commemoration for its founding.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In Tasmania, Regatta Day occurred initially in December to mark the anniversary of the landing of Abel Tasman.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] South Australia celebrated Proclamation Day on 28 December.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Western Australia had its own Foundation Day (now Western Australia Day) on 1 June.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1888, all colonial capitals except Adelaide celebrated "Anniversary Day".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1910, South Australia adopted 26 January as "Foundation Day", to replace another holiday known as Accession Day, which had been held on 22 January to mark the accession to the throne of King Edward VII, who died in May 1910.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The first Australia Day was established in response to Australia's involvement in World War I.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1915, Ellen "Ellie" Wharton Kirke MBE, née Clements, mother of four servicemen, thought up the idea of a national day, with the specific aim of raising funds for wounded soldiers, and the term was coined to stir up patriotic feelings.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1915 a committee to celebrate Australia Day was formed, and the date chosen was 30 July, on which many fund-raising efforts were run to support the war effort.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] It was also held in July in subsequent years of World War I: on 28 July 1916, 27 July 1917, and 26 July 1918.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The idea of a national day to be celebrated on 26 January was slow to catch on, partly because of competition with Anzac Day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Victoria adopted 26 January as Australia Day in 1931, and by 1935, all states of Australia were celebrating 26 January as Australia Day (although it was still known as Anniversary Day in New South Wales).
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The name "Foundation Day" persisted in local usage.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The 150th anniversary of British settlement in Australia in 1938 was widely celebrated.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Preparations began in 1936 with the formation of a Celebrations Council.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In that year, New South Wales was the only state to abandon the traditional long weekend, and the annual Anniversary Day public holiday was held on the anniversary day – Wednesday 26 January.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] However, it was also a declared a Day of Mourning by the Aborigines Progressive Association and the Australian Aborigines League as a protest against the "Whiteman's seizure of our country".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The Commonwealth and state governments agreed to unify the celebrations on 26 January as "Australia Day" in 1946, although the public holiday was instead taken on the Monday closest to the anniversary.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The *Nationality and Citizenship Act 1948* came into effect on 26 January 1949, creating Australian citizenship for the first time.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Previously, Australian nationals were simply British subjects alongside all other members of Commonwealth of Nations; now they were both British subjects and Australian citizens.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Historian Ken Inglis wrote in 1967 that Australia Day was not celebrated publicly in Canberra at that time.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1988, the celebration of 200 years since the arrival of the First Fleet was organised on a large scale as the Australian Bicentenary, with many significant events taking place in all major cities.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Over 2.5 million people attended the event in Sydney.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] These included street parties, concerts, including performances on the steps and forecourt of the Sydney Opera House and at many other public venues, art and literary competitions, historic re-enactments, and the opening of the Powerhouse Museum at its new location.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] A re-enactment of the arrival of the First Fleet took place in Sydney Harbour, with ships that had sailed from Portsmouth a year earlier taking part.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The various celebrations and civic ceremonies such as citizenship ceremonies, the Australian of the Year awards and the Australia Day Honours (introduced in 1975) started being performed on Australia Day from around the 1950s.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] After 1988, participation in Australia Day increased, and in 1994 all states and territories began to celebrate a unified public holiday on 26 January – regardless of the day of the week – for the first time.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Previously, some states had celebrated the public holiday on a Monday or Friday to provide a long weekend.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Research conducted in 2007 reported that 28% of Australians polled attended an organised Australia Day event and a further 26% celebrated with family and friends.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] This reflected the results of an earlier research project where 66% of respondents anticipated that they would actively celebrate Australia Day 2005.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Outdoor concerts, community barbecues, sports competitions, festivals and fireworks are some of the many events held in communities across Australia.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] These official events are presented by the National Australia Day Council, an official council or committee in each state and territory, and local committees.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In Sydney, the harbour is a focus and boat races are held, such as a ferry race and the tall ships race.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In Adelaide, the key celebrations are "Australia Day in the City" involving a parade, concert and fireworks display held in Elder Park, with a new outdoor art installation in 2019 designed to acknowledge, remember and recognise Aboriginal people who have contributed to the community.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Featuring the People's March and the Voyages Concert, Melbourne's events focus strongly on the celebration of multiculturalism.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In Perth, for many years until 2022, the Skyworks were the largest single event presented each Australia Day; the display was replaced by a more modest one coupled with a drone show the following year.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Since 2012, with the exceptions of 2015 and 2020–22, a Big Blue match between Melbourne Victory FC and Sydney FC has been played annually on Australia Day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Citizenship ceremonies are also commonly held, with Australia Day now the largest occasion for the acquisition of Australian citizenship.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] On 26 January 2011, more than 300 citizenship ceremonies took place and around 13,000 people from 143 countries took Australian citizenship.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In recent years many citizenship ceremonies have included an affirmation by existing citizens.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Research conducted in 2007 reported that 78.6% of respondents thought that citizenship ceremonies were an important feature of the day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In September 2019, the Morrison government amended the *Australian Citizenship Ceremonies Code* to require local councils to hold a citizenship ceremony on Australia Day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The official Australia Day Ambassador Program supports celebrations in communities across the nation by facilitating the participation of high-achieving Australians in local community celebrations.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 2011, 385 ambassadors participated in 384 local community celebrations.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The Order of Australia awards are also a feature of the day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The Australia Day Achievement Medallion is awarded to citizens by local governments based on excellence in both government and non-government organisations.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The governor-general and prime minister both address the nation.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] On the eve of Australia Day each year, the Prime Minister announces the winner of the Australian of the Year award, presented to an Australian citizen who has shown a "significant contribution to the Australian community and nation" and is an "inspirational role model for the Australian community".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Subcategories of the award include Young Australian of the Year and Senior Australian of the Year, and an award for Australia's Local Hero.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Research in 2009 indicated that Australians reflect on history and future fairly equally on Australia Day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Of those polled, 43% agreed that history is the most important thing to think about on Australia Day and 41% said they look towards "our future", while 13% thought it was important to "think about the present at this time" and 3% were unsure.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Despite the date reflecting the arrival of the First Fleet, contemporary celebrations are not particularly historical in their theme.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] There are no large-scale re-enactments and the national leader's participation is focused largely on events such as the Australian of the Year Awards announcement and Citizenship Ceremonies.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] A similar proportion (89%) agreed that "it is important to recognise the cultural diversity of the nation".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Some Australians regard Australia Day as a symbol of the adverse impacts of British settlement on Australia's Indigenous peoples.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 1888, prior to the first centennial anniversary of the First Fleet landing on 26 January 1788, New South Wales premier Henry Parkes was asked about inclusion of Aboriginal people in the celebrations.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The 150th anniversary celebrations in 1938 were accompanied by an Aboriginal Day of Mourning, declared by the Aborigines Progressive Association and the Australian Aborigines League as a protest against the "Whiteman's seizure of our country".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] At the bicentennial celebrations in 1988, large gathering of Aboriginal people in Sydney led an "Invasion Day" commemoration marking the loss of Indigenous culture.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Some Indigenous figures and others continue to label Australia Day as "Invasion Day", and protests occur almost every year, sometimes at Australia Day events.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Thousands of people participate in protest marches in capital cities on Australia Day; estimates for the 2018 protest in Melbourne ranged into tens of thousands.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The anniversary is also termed by some as "Survival Day" and marked by events such as the Survival Day concert, first held in Sydney in 1992, celebrating the fact that the Indigenous people and culture have survived despite colonisation and discrimination.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] In 2016, National Indigenous Television chose the name "Survival Day" as its preferred choice on the basis that it acknowledges the mixed nature of the day, saying that the term "recognises the invasion", but does not allow that to frame the entire story of the Aboriginal people.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] The ceremony was directed by Rhoda Roberts from 2003 until 2013.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] It has continued under a new name, WugulOra, which means "one mob".
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Several major employers, both public and private, including the Australian Public Service, permit employees to work on Australia Day and take another day off.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] Extensive polling on the naming and observance of the day has been conducted over the years, with varying results depending on the question and the pollster.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] A January 2026 Roy Morgan poll found 72% support for the name and 60.5% support for the date of the day.
[src:australian-football-international/australia-day] A poll taken for *The Sydney Morning Herald* found majority support for Australia Day on its date in every generation.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] The **Australian Football Harmony Cup** is an amateur Australian rules football competition featuring teams drawn from Melbourne's migrant communities.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] The tournament is coordinated by Australian Football International.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] It was first held in 2004 in Melbourne around National Harmony Day.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] Australian Football is also known for a high participation rate amongst migrants, particularly amongst Europeans.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] Many such players reach the highest levels and some like Ron Barassi, Stephen Silvagni, Robert DiPierdomenico and Alex Jesaulenko are legends of the game.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] Some Australian Football League clubs, such as Carlton are renowned for the high number of players of Mediterranean origin.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] The Harmony Cup has included teams representing multicultural communities from Albania, Chile, Croatia, Israel, Ireland, Greece, Italy, Lebanon, Malta, Macedonia, Netherlands, New Zealand, Poland, Samoa, South Sudan, Spain, Switzerland, Tonga, Wales, Vietnam and Turkey.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] A side drawn from the Melbourne Aboriginal community has also competed at the Harmony Cup.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] Teams under the banner of "United Nations", "Team Harmony" and "Team Africa" have also competed at the Harmony Cup.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] The first Harmony Cup was held in 2004 at Skinner Reserve, Braybrook in 2004, with Israel 8.9 (57) defeating Samoa 1.0 (6) in the Grand Final.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] The 2005 Harmony Cup was won by Greece 5.5 (35) over Turkey 3.3 (21) in front of a crowd of 2,300 at Optus Oval in Carlton, Melbourne.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-harmony-cup] The Harmony Cup returned in 2010 and has been held **every year** since.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-international] The AFI hosts and supports Aussie rules matches in various countries, with the nine-a-side sport played on soccer, rugby and gridiron pitches, with both contact and non-contact versions of the game.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-international] It has also developed the Australian Football Harmony Cup, which has been played annually in Melbourne since 2010 between teams from migrant communities.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-international] Australian Football International's headquarters are in Melbourne, Australia.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-international] AFI's CEO is Brian Clarke and its board includes high-profile former AFL players Ron Barassi, Allen Aylett and Brian Dixon.
[src:australian-football-international/australian-football-international] The organisation has no official relationship with the Australian Football League, which has hosted its own shortened variation of the sport AFLX.
